{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651826"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:28:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:28:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18496"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18496"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.66,0,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11225"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11225"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65294"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26312"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe heart has three principal surfaces that correspond to their anatomical relationships with nearby structures in the thorax.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the anterior (sternocostal) surface of the heart?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Consists mainly of the left ventricle","Consists mainly of the right ventricle","Lies directly on the diaphragm","Faces towards the vertebral column","Consists mainly of the left atrium"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior surface of the heart \u003Cstrong\u003Econsists mainly of the right ventricle\u003C/strong\u003E. This surface lies behind the sternum and ribs, creating the characteristic cardiac silhouette seen on chest radiographs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe alternative descriptions are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsists mainly of the left ventricle\u003C/strong\u003E - The left ventricle predominantly forms the inferior surface and contributes to the posterior surface\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELies directly on the diaphragm\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the inferior (diaphragmatic) surface which contacts the central tendon\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaces towards the vertebral column\u003C/strong\u003E - The posterior (pulmonary) surface faces the lungs and vertebral column\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsists mainly of the left atrium\u003C/strong\u003E - The left atrium contributes to the posterior surface near the pulmonary veins\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis anatomical arrangement allows the right ventricle to be accessed during cardiac examination through the anterior chest wall.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The anterior (sternocostal) surface of the heart consists mainly of the right ventricle and faces the chest wall.","The inferior (diaphragmatic) surface of the heart sits on the diaphragm\u0027s central tendon and comprises the left ventricle and part of the right ventricle.","The posterior (pulmonary) surface of the heart faces the lungs and consists primarily of the left chambers."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65294"}}